      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. so with the arm, how much of a jump are we talking about usually? like if the market goes up a bit, is it gonna be a small change or could the payments totally spiral out of control? im just really worried about things being unpredictable.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Typically, ARMs accumulate rate increments of 2% to 3% per adjustment period, meaning your monthly payment could jump by hundreds of dollars within a few years if rates rise. While they can't spiral instantly without refinancing or default, missing payments due to this jump is a genuine risk that can lead to financial instability. Personal lenders might anger or cut off your current lender service if you miss payments due to unforeseen circumstances. Given your desire to avoid unpredictability, many experts suggest fixating your loan or earthing yourself financially now. Ultimately, your home value doesn't decrease just because your payments do, so ensuring you can afford the worst-case scenario is key.",
